      "content": "The point where the principal starts to drop significantly is often referred to as the \"break-even point.\" This is the point where the interest paid equals the principal paid, and the balance starts to decrease more rapidly.\n\nTo calculate the break-even point, you can use a formula or consult the amortization schedule. The break-even point is usually around 2-3 years after the initial loan period, but it can vary depending on the interest rate and loan terms.\n\nIn your case, since you're making full payments every month, you can expect the break-even point to be relatively early. As a rough estimate, you can assume that the break-even point will be around 1-2 years after the initial loan period.\n\nTo determine when you've actually turned the corner, look for the following:\n\n* The interest paid as a percentage of the balance starts to decrease significantly. This is usually around the break-even point.\n* The principal paid as a percentage of the balance starts to increase significantly. This is usually around the break-even point.\n* The balance starts to decrease more rapidly. This is usually around the break-even point.\n\nKeep in mind that the break-even point is just an estimate, and the actual point where you've turned the corner may vary",
